Is Emanuel here yet?

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:28.100
&gt;&gt; No.

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:29.400
&gt;&gt; He is not?

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:32.800
Well, he's the [laughter] we
have a longstanding relationship

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:36.920
with the Director of the Italian
Culture Institute as well

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:38.360
as with the Embassy of Italy.

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:41.220
And we're grateful
for that relationship

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:44.010
and its continuation.

00:03:44.010 --> 00:03:48.260
Let me turn to Dr. Ceriani.

00:03:51.530 --> 00:03:54.710
Who I, who I will
invite up in a second.

00:03:54.710 --> 00:03:56.620
But I put my notes
about his career,

00:03:56.620 --> 00:03:59.010
it's too long for
me to remember.

00:03:59.010 --> 00:04:01.710
[Laughter] He's an Assistant
Professor of Musicology

00:04:01.710 --> 00:04:04.190
at the Department of
Music at Rowan University.

00:04:04.190 --> 00:04:06.020
That's in Glassboro, New Jersey.

00:04:06.020 --> 00:04:10.440
He received his Ph.D. in
Musicology from Harvard in 2011.

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:13.640
Dr. Ceriani earned his degree
in saxophone at the Conservatory

00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:16.550
at Bologna, in his
native Italy in 1999.

00:04:16.550 --> 00:04:20.860
And is Laurea Cum Laude at the
University of Florence in 2003.

00:04:20.860 --> 00:04:26.080
Throughout the 1990s and early
2000s, he performed extensively

00:04:26.080 --> 00:04:30.630
as a saxophone player in Italy,
France, and the United States.

00:04:30.630 --> 00:04:35.240
Prior to working at Rowan, he
spent two years, 2011 to '13,

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:38.540
as a Mellon Postdoctoral Fellow
in the Department of Music

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:40.450
at Columbia University.

00:04:40.450 --> 00:04:44.510
Please help me in welcoming
Dr. Ceriani to the-- .

00:04:44.510 --> 00:04:53.070
[ Applause ]

00:04:53.070 --> 00:04:55.380
&gt;&gt; Dr. Davide Ceriani:
Alright, thank you.

00:04:55.380 --> 00:04:56.900
&gt;&gt; Dr. John Haskell:
Let me start

00:04:56.900 --> 00:04:59.570
with a very general question

00:04:59.570 --> 00:05:01.340
so that we can learn
a little bit more

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:03.400
about the star of
the show tonight.

00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:04.930
Where are you from?

00:05:04.930 --> 00:05:06.710
Tell us a little bit
about your background.

00:05:06.710 --> 00:05:09.020
&gt;&gt; Dr. Davide Ceriani: So
originally from Florence.

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:14.260
And so I lived there
throughout high school.

00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:15.560
And then at some point,

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:18.240
even though I was attending
the University of Florence.

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:20.420
But then I started
moving around.

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:24.980
And so through these
European Union programs,

00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:29.160
the [foreign language] I lived
in France and Germany a bit.

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:31.890
And then here in
the United States.

00:05:31.890 --> 00:05:37.050
And as a part of this constant
journey for both personal

00:05:37.050 --> 00:05:40.130
and professional reasons.

00:05:40.130 --> 00:05:44.920
I realized that though there
were three words, I would say.

00:05:44.920 --> 00:05:48.920
Three concepts that
always stood with me.

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:50.970
And they were like
identity, first.

00:05:50.970 --> 00:05:54.330
And that is who you are and
how you define yourself.

00:05:54.330 --> 00:05:59.090
Depending on how
[inaudible] whatever you go.

00:05:59.090 --> 00:06:02.820
Then a matter of alterity,
that is being the other.

00:06:02.820 --> 00:06:06.760
How the others view
you in this new context

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:09.410
where you decide to, to live.

00:06:09.410 --> 00:06:10.910
And then acceptance.

00:06:10.910 --> 00:06:14.660
That is how you negotiate
with the issue

00:06:14.660 --> 00:06:16.890
of identity and alterity.

00:06:16.890 --> 00:06:20.860
So your identity
versus who you are

00:06:20.860 --> 00:06:23.900
versus what this
new environment is.

00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:30.560
And to an extent, I
would say this became

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:31.920
autobiographical research.

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:35.370
Because I realized that
Italians immigrating here.

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:37.120
Although in a totally
different context

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:39.430
but did a very similar thing.

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:42.420
&gt;&gt; Dr. John Haskell: So you,
I guess it goes without saying

00:06:42.420 --> 00:06:44.850
that you, that you
developed an interest,

00:06:44.850 --> 00:06:46.750
an intense interest in opera.

00:06:46.750 --> 00:06:49.530
And you know, United States,
when you're a boy growing

00:06:49.530 --> 00:06:51.570
up like my father
used to take me.

00:06:51.570 --> 00:06:54.040
Before I can even
remember, to baseball games

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:55.710
at old D.C. Stadium here.

00:06:55.710 --> 00:06:58.600
So somehow or another, he was
inculcating this obsession

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:00.150
with baseball that
continues to today.

00:07:00.150 --> 00:07:02.250
For no particularly good reason.

00:07:02.250 --> 00:07:04.670
How did you get involved
in opera?

00:07:04.670 --> 00:07:05.970
Was it, was it something

00:07:05.970 --> 00:07:07.900
that your parents
groomed you into that?

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:10.700
&gt;&gt; Dr. Davide Ceriani: No,
not at all, [inaudible].

00:07:10.700 --> 00:07:14.700
I have nothing to do or
really do with the music.

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:18.100
My father has a vague interest
in opera, but not really.

00:07:18.100 --> 00:07:20.730
No, I wasn't really one of
these kids who start playing

00:07:20.730 --> 00:07:22.180
at the age of five, six.

00:07:22.180 --> 00:07:24.350
No, it took me quite,
quite a while.

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:26.790
Around 16 I started playing.

00:07:26.790 --> 00:07:29.760
In particular, saxophone
[inaudible] earlier,

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:31.060
some beginning.

00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:34.090
It wasn't even an
interest in opera.

00:07:34.090 --> 00:07:35.980
I listened to opera,
but not really

00:07:35.980 --> 00:07:37.620
as a professional interest.

00:07:37.620 --> 00:07:42.600
And then by going to the
conservatory, by playing,

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:47.780
I started meeting singers,
attending opera performances,

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:50.400
and that's how it all started.

00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:53.780
Even though I have to
say by going abroad

00:07:53.780 --> 00:07:58.040
and having people
asking me about opera,

00:07:58.040 --> 00:07:59.900
the operatic repertory
especially.

00:07:59.900 --> 00:08:04.990
The Italian composers, and
again, made me even more aware

00:08:04.990 --> 00:08:08.210
of how the others
viewed me as an Italian.

00:08:08.210 --> 00:08:11.210
As sort of interested in
opera perhaps by default.

00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:13.520
And so that kind of
vague interest I had

00:08:13.520 --> 00:08:15.990
in the beginning developed
in something, yeah, more.

00:08:15.990 --> 00:08:17.290
&gt;&gt; Dr. John Haskell:

00:08:17.290 --> 00:08:22.480
You obviously grew a good
crowd with the topic.

00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:24.650
So maybe this is an
obvious question.

00:08:24.650 --> 00:08:26.700
But I'd like to hear
your answers to,

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:29.690
to why what you're working
on here at the Library.

00:08:29.690 --> 00:08:32.240
And why the topic of
this, this session.

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:34.260
Why do you think
that's important to us?

00:08:34.260 --> 00:08:35.560
What, why does that matter?

00:08:35.560 --> 00:08:38.380
&gt;&gt; Dr. Davide Ceriani: Well
I mean, it's important mainly

00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:43.780
to better discuss
crucial period in history

00:08:43.780 --> 00:08:46.130
of migration to this country.

00:08:46.130 --> 00:08:49.420
Of course the, the
history of Italy.

00:08:49.420 --> 00:08:54.200
But also because I realized that
in the secondary literature.

00:08:54.200 --> 00:09:00.050
That there was a lot on the
socioeconomic accomplishments

00:09:00.050 --> 00:09:02.320
of the Italians here in the US.

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:07.080
But not really as much
about opera itself.

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:13.850
In other words, so when,
when Italians came here.

00:09:13.850 --> 00:09:15.950
They pretty much worked through.

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:19.570
So for example, they,
they brought

00:09:19.570 --> 00:09:21.710
with them their own language.

00:09:21.710 --> 00:09:23.840
Which is of course
an important factor

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:25.820
in defining your own identity.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:28.510
But it can also be
an isolating factor.

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:31.430
And indeed, some of them
kind of isolated themselves

00:09:31.430 --> 00:09:32.730
in these Little Italies,

00:09:32.730 --> 00:09:34.680
and didn't even need
to, to get out of them.

00:09:34.680 --> 00:09:37.920
Food, of course, it's
another important topic.

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:42.140
And you're going to start
a few books that I read,

00:09:42.140 --> 00:09:44.330
I started for this research.

00:09:44.330 --> 00:09:47.930
Simona Frasca, for example has
written some wonderful essays

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:51.400
on the importance of food.

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:56.000
Simona Frasca wrote this
book on The Diaspora

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.540
of Neapolitan Musicians
in New York.

00:09:59.540 --> 00:10:03.100
Although she, as many
other major scholars

00:10:03.100 --> 00:10:05.560
of Italian music in the US.

00:10:05.560 --> 00:10:10.370
They primarily focused on the
Neapolitan repertory in the US.

00:10:10.370 --> 00:10:13.640
This popular repertory
which was hugely successful.

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:15.500
She one chapter on Caruso.

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:22.070
But Caruso primarily performing
these Neapolitan songs.

00:10:22.070 --> 00:10:25.200
So I realized that there
was a spot missing there.

00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:28.650
It was exactly what opera
meant for the Italians.

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:30.370
Particularly in the Northeast.

00:10:30.370 --> 00:10:33.780
I would say Boston through
Washington, which was the area

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:37.620
where Italians primarily lived.

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:40.430
So that's how I realized
it was very important.

00:10:40.430 --> 00:10:44.650
And Library of Congress had
huge amount of materials to, to,

00:10:44.650 --> 00:10:46.370
to work on this topic.

00:10:46.370 --> 00:10:49.370
&gt;&gt; Dr. John Haskell: So are
there other specific ways that,

00:10:49.370 --> 00:10:51.880
that, that opera was
relevant to immigrants?

00:10:51.880 --> 00:10:55.880
And, and, and before
that, you, you,

00:10:55.880 --> 00:10:57.960
I guess generally the
mass migration is what?

00:10:57.960 --> 00:10:59.260
Eighteen-eighty or so?

00:10:59.260 --> 00:11:01.620
In, into the, getting
into the early

00:11:01.620 --> 00:11:03.680
to middle decades
of the 20th century.

00:11:03.680 --> 00:11:05.490
What in particular.

00:11:05.490 --> 00:11:06.830
Did opera mean anything

00:11:06.830 --> 00:11:09.170
in the United States
before Italians came?

00:11:09.170 --> 00:11:10.840
&gt;&gt; Dr. Davide Ceriani:
I would say it did,

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:14.650
but it, in a different way.

00:11:14.650 --> 00:11:22.380
So before the, the, the 1880s,
1870s, Americans had this sort

00:11:22.380 --> 00:11:27.050
of dreamy romantic view of
Italy, thanks to some diaries

00:11:27.050 --> 00:11:29.550
of Americans who
traveled through Italy.

00:11:29.550 --> 00:11:31.490
And so they, they wrote them.

00:11:31.490 --> 00:11:33.800
And lot of people
here read about it.

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:38.150
So [inaudible] came up with
these great quote [inaudible].

00:11:38.150 --> 00:11:41.160
After the 19th century,
classical buildings of Greece

00:11:41.160 --> 00:11:45.120
and Rome exerted a strong
fascination on American artists,

00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:48.830
courthouses, state
legislatures, railroad stations.

00:11:48.830 --> 00:11:52.560
And the dwellings of
the wealthy were erected

00:11:52.560 --> 00:11:54.360
with the imposing-pillared
facades.

00:11:54.360 --> 00:11:57.870
And pediments that characterized
Greek and Roman temples.

00:11:57.870 --> 00:12:01.350
And for example there were even
not only American architects

00:12:01.350 --> 00:12:04.240
were influenced by the
architecture of Italy.

00:12:04.240 --> 00:12:06.670
But some Italian
artists came here.

00:12:06.670 --> 00:12:08.830
[Inaudible], for example,
came here with the idea

00:12:08.830 --> 00:12:10.530
of building a big
statue of Washington.

00:12:10.530 --> 00:12:12.200
He came up with this
[inaudible] he failed

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:16.410
to secure all the
necessary funds.

00:12:16.410 --> 00:12:18.620
Brumidi was the author of
the fresco of the "Apotheosis

00:12:18.620 --> 00:12:23.050
of Washington, Here in
the US capital next door.

00:12:23.050 --> 00:12:27.850
And the first performance
of an opera in its entirety,

00:12:27.850 --> 00:12:30.810
in its original language
was [inaudible].

00:12:30.810 --> 00:12:33.910
It was Rossini, The
Barber of Seville,

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:37.290
[inaudible] Le Barbier de
Séville, more or less, okay?

00:12:37.290 --> 00:12:39.050
We get what, what it is.

00:12:39.050 --> 00:12:43.080
And following that performance,

00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:46.380
many other major cultural
figures in New York,

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:48.240
including of course the
[inaudible] the author

00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:50.370
of the librettos for three

00:12:50.370 --> 00:12:55.000
of most important Mozart
operas promoted this art form.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:59.540
And eventually these
[inaudible] became more

00:12:59.540 --> 00:13:02.800
and more popular type
of entertainment.

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:04.530
This book, Opera on the Road.

00:13:04.530 --> 00:13:05.830
&gt;&gt; Dr. John Haskell: This is,

00:13:05.830 --> 00:13:07.130
this is well before
the, the mass migration?

00:13:07.130 --> 00:13:08.430
&gt;&gt; Dr. Davide Ceriani:
Yes, absolutely.

00:13:08.430 --> 00:13:10.540
And the importance
of these two books

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:14.400
of casting opera before
the mass migration is that.

00:13:14.400 --> 00:13:16.770
So Katherine Preston
basically argues that

00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:19.920
and quite convincingly
that the American elite,

00:13:19.920 --> 00:13:25.360
especially New York, tried
to make opera an elitist sort

00:13:25.360 --> 00:13:27.390
of type of entertainment.

00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:32.780
But they failed because they
essentially they did not have

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:34.080
enough wealth.

00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:36.840
Enough money to run the
operas by themselves.

00:13:36.840 --> 00:13:39.810
And because here the
state support that existed

00:13:39.810 --> 00:13:42.540
in Europe did not exist.

00:13:42.540 --> 00:13:45.820
Then they had to draw
in a lot of the people,

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:48.780
the poorer people, making
the prices affordable.

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:50.230
And [inaudible] argues

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:52.770
that there was democracy
